author: Richa1

description.text:
Bearing holder for 608ZZ 22mm x 7 mm. bore =8mm

printed in ABS 0.2mm resolution

Golden Ratio Snowfake

This model is an entry for the BlocksCAD Snowflake Challenge

To design this model I was inspired in the golden ratio. This ratio is common in nature, and can be found in places such as the arrangement of different parts of the leaves of some plants or even in the human genome DNA.

In this particular model, all the segments are multiples of the golden ratio, which is roughly 1.61803. I will provide a document showing this on the model so it is easier to understand (In the document only the exact proportions for the first version are shown, however v2 and v3 are very similar). You can also download the .xml file to see how I implemented it to BlocksCAD

I had some problems with the .stl that was automatically generated in BlocksCAD when I tried to slice it in Simplify 3D and in Cura. However, it was easily solved by using a stl repairing software. I think that the origin of this problem is the design itself, since it may have some intersecting faces, or something like that.

title: OTTO DIY with 48:1 DC Motors
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
OTTO robot with 48:1 DC Motors

List of parts:
I used a 3.7V 1200mAH LIPO and a new DC MOTOR driver NANO SHIELD PCB
You can use a Arduino NANO with I/O shield and a L9110S H-bridge Dual driver (some modifactions to the sketch will be required)
Small female to female jumper wires
Buzzer
2 x DAGU 48:1 DC Motors (yellow DC motors with right-angled gearboxes)
HC-SR04 Ultrasound sensor module
MAX 7219 LED matrix module
2 x Screws - small self tapping screws to secure PCB in place
4 x Screws - 3mm x 15mm screws with 3mm nuts (to secure castor and motor clamp in place)
You can use a 3.7V 1200mAH LIPO and a 5 volt DC to DC booster

CONNECTIONS:
The HC-SR04 Ultrasound sensor is connected (TRIG to pin 8 and ECHO to pin 9)
The MAX 7219 LED matrix is connected (CLK to pin 11, DIN to pin 12, CS to pin 10)
The BUZZER is connected (pin 13),
The Left Motor PWM pin is pin 6,
The Left Motor DIRECTION pin is pin 2,
The Right Motor PWM pin is pin 5,
The Right Motor DIRECTION pin is pin 4,

Code and libraries are :
https://github.com/jarsoftelectrical/OTTO-DC-Motor

Check the OTTO DIY+ for more details as this is based on that project.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2398231

For the Arduino programming:
Download & Install Arduino IDE:
https://www.arduino.cc/

This is still work in progress,

author: stunner2211

description.text:
Simples is an indoor flying wing designed by Mike Bell. Hopefully the plan will appear soon in RCME magazine. If you're interested here's a quick video of 2 of these flying https://youtu.be/SF22Q8c-42s
These 3d printed parts were used to make assembly easier on the models Mike and myself have built and flown.
Receiver Mounts
The Hobbyking receiver is held in by 3 screws, the Spektrum receivers are held in by 4 screws. The Spektrum receivers have 2 thicknesses of PCB, make sure you print the right one for yours. They are both printed in PLA at a layer height of 0.1mm and 100% fill. The screws came from a pack of spectacle repair screws I obtained from Ebay at a very respectable price. The mounts can be glued into the model before fastening in the receiver.
Motor Mounts
Mike used a brushless motor and the radial mount. I used the brushed Parkzone P51 motor/gearbox on the beam mount. The radial mount will need drilling out for the correct hole spacing. For the Parkzone motor I cut off the spikes and drilled the lugs for a screw at each side and drilled the printed mount to match, again using small screws to hold it them together. Both mounts are glued into place before final attachment of the motors. Both were printed in PLA at a layer height of 0.1mm at 100% fill
Control horns
These will need turning through 90deg in Cura to lie flat. I put 6 onto Cura and printed them so I have a few spares if needed. The holes will probably need drilling out to suit the pushrods. Again printed in PLA at a layer height of 0.1mm at 100% fill.
UPDATE 02/02/18 -
Motor mount Mk2 (Parkzone) Same size and settings as the original but with the cut through for location on the inside edge rather than the middle which makes it easier to fit :o)
CNC cut Simples version photos - I only have a small CNC machine (table size 240 x 190mm) and to get it cut on there I've drawn Simples in Fusion 360 and split it into 3 parts with jigsaw type joints. Yes, I know it's probably quicker to cut a Simples from sheet depron but where's the fun in that :o) Finished photos shows the colour scheme. The sharp eyed among you will notice the painted finished version is different to the unpainted. A late decision to leave off the rudder .... ok so i messed up the paint work on the first version ... the benefits of CNC cutting, just press the button and out pops another one :o)

WIP

05/01/2017 added cannon support (not finished)

title: Harmonic Drive (Nema 23) 3D-printable
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Intro:
For my final exams i am constructing, printing and building a 6-axis robotic arm in style of the UR robot arms ("universal robots").
Since original harmonic drive gearings are too expensive for me (one costs about 600€) im trying to build my own version.

Im using 6mm steel softair BBs for the flexible bearing inside of the gearing.

I already printed an approx. model of the gearing, which even works (handdriven).
However this project is still work in progress and i will add everything in the next few days.

UPDATE: i have built a first prototype (check the photo), but i didnt like the way the bearings work, they were not precise enough to fulfill my quality standards. I therefore redesigned the mounting cylinder, enclosure and bearings. first i tried to fix the inner rings of the bearings with a thread on the mounting cylinder which didnt work either, at least not if im printing with a 0,8mm nozzle. In order to press the inner rings of the bearings on the mounting cylinder im now using the same holes im using to transfer the radial forces from the mounting cylinder to the flexspline. Also i updated all other files here on thingi.

OLD UPDATE: I updated the following Files: "Lagerkäfig Flexkugellager", "Lagerkäfig Schrägkugellager", "Gehäuse", "Motorhalterung".

OLD UPDATE: I now created a more detailed version of the gearing which is compatible with Nema 23 motors. I will now check if everything works out but it takes some time to print...

OLD UPDATE: My Nema 17 Motor isnt powerful enough to drive the gearing yet. I will check if a nema 23 Motor which is compatible with the ustepper motor driver or radds motor driver, delivers enough power. Otherwise i will add a planetary gearing ontop of the nema 23 or go with another motor driver.

Ultimaker

This Thing is meant to be a "rack and pinion type thing" to replace the lower belt drive on a Printrbot. The rubber belt can stretch over time and crack or dry out easily from the heat of the bed. Align it with your lower Y-Axis Stepper Motor, and screw in place with three screws. Place two of these in series for a full length Get-Rid-Of-Belts-On-Printrbot-Thing!!

• Print out two pieces with 100% infill and 0.27 mm resolution or better.
    Sand down rough edges with fine grit sandpaper where necessary. We need to make sure we have a smooth surface here or else we will get jittery prints.

  • Remove old belt drive on bottom of Printrbot (Y-Axis belt) as well as the washer tensioner Thing (This will be in the way for the new parts).

  • Align new printed parts in place with existing gear (on the left side of the belt), and fasten to printrbot with screws making sure not to screw into heated bed. Determine correct length screws for your printer BEFORE screwing.

  • Move bed forward and backwards to determine if it is adjusted properly and straight.

  • Once straight, VOILA! You now have a thing to create more accurate parts and to get rid of those annoying belts that always stretch and get too loose!!
    • Bryan-Enjoy!

title: Ball jointed cable management for Prusa MK2S/Zaribo heated bed

description.text:
This is a ball jointed cable management system for the heated bed on Prusa i3 MK2s and Zaribo 3d Printers. Note that the MK2S adaptor is coming soon so this is only currently usable for the Zaribo printer. For more information on Zaribo click here - http://zaribo.org/

The same system will be coming shortly for the extruder and Z motor cables.

There are 3 main elements to this system:

  1. The heatbed cover which is made up of 2 pieces. A 12mm M3 screw is required but you can use the hex nut from the existing heatbed cover. Oh and you will need to remove the heatbed cable connectors as they will not fit through the ball joints, they are easy to screw on/off though.
    These must be printed in the orientation of the supplied STLS and will require support. Use medium density support for a better finish.

  2. Ball joints - Approximately 15 of these will be required for the Zaribo but it will depend on the length of your cables. These are printed using 'Spiralise' or 'Vase' mode without any top or bottom layers. I recommend that these be printed with PETG so they have a little flex.

  3. The Rambo box adaptor - Zaribo - This is similar to the ball joints but is straight on one end so it can fit over the existing Rambo connection, it should be a tight-ish fit.
    This adaptor must also be printed using 'Spiralise' or 'Vase' mode. I recommend that these be printed with PETG so they have a little flex.

When the ball joints are pushed together they should be quite a loose fit but not fall apart.

TIPS: When threading the wires through the ball joints, do it in segments to make it easier then just joint the segments together afterwards.

Just a simple pencilsharpener for two sizes of pencils. This model is non-functional except for the fun part :)

I modelled this on a 1:1 scale from a real sharpener and printed this 400% the actual size.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15 for blade, 0.20 for base

Infill:

10% - 15%

Notes:

Only the blade needs some raft/brim to make sure it keeps sticking to your printbed. Print the blade on a 45 degree angle for nice lines on your blades. Make sure to rotate the blade with the correct side down. OnShape does some weird things with top/bottom orientation.

You need one base and two blades.

Printed the blades in Prusa PLA (Silver) and the base in Colorfab NGEN Gray Metallic for a nice immitation of aluminium and steel.
Glue the blades on the base and add two screws to complete the sharpener. You can also drill two tiny holes in the base. Pick your screws according to the scale you print this in.

Created with OnShape using a calliper and protractor

The STL's and the OnShape link contain a version that has better alignment of the small cone.

https://cad.onshape.com/documents/05c23aaf0aff95be686b85fa/w/4ae1c63fb4fb79de0755e8e7/e/e7e4ffc907ee931d70f5c75b

This item is used for quick, safe and cheap healing of common cold.
HOW TO USE:
Just fill it by the bigger hole with warm water (just enough to be comfortable). Then pour half a teaspoon of table salt into it. Mix it. Then pour the water in one of your nose hole ,while breathing with your mouth. Let it all run through your nose and repeat after 2-3 hours.

Now with precise measure spoon for salt (one of this spoons per one nose kettle)

comments.text: If you need to use tap water boil it first at least 10 minutes and let it cool down and then mix with salt and use when is at body temperature or a litlle bit warmer .
comments.author: canibalu

comments.text: I would add an important note, do NOT use municipal tap water as it is full of chloramines that will injure the nasal tissue more than the original infection.  I've had first-hand experience and its a burning, painful sensation.   Also non-municipal tap water runs the small but deadly risk of Naegleria infection.  Bottom line, ONLY use filtered or purified water.  For municipal water I use a Britta water filter.  I like to warm the water first in the microwave (mildly warm, NOT hot).  The salt dissolves quicker and it is more comfortable and effective in the nasal passages.

title: Flying Wing
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a Flying Wing, designed by Daniel of rctestflight (youtube.com/user/rctestflight).

It's a composite model, utilizing 3D printing, traditional balsawood and carbon spars.
You can see the model in action in the youtube video at the bottom (flight around 1:18, don't know how to put the video into the overview box above).

DISCLAIMER:
I currently haven't build this Wing myself.
Daniel sent me his only CAD model of the wing.
I slightly modified the CAD model, exported all the 3D printable parts as STLs (modified their origin so that they are oriented correctly in the Slicer after importing) and took several days to create a comprehensible plan.
THIS IS NOT A BEGINNERS PROJECT!!
Knowledge on building traditional model airplanes is highly recommended!

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:
  • 5x Leading Edge Spar Bracket Left.stl
  • 5x Leading Edge Spar Bracket Right.stl
  • 6x Center Spar Bracket Left.stl
  • 6x Center Spar Bracket Right.stl
  • 1x Middle Spar Bracket Left.stl
  • 1x Middle Spar Bracket Right.stl
  • 1x Tip Center Spar Bracket Left.stl
  • 1x Tip Center Spar Bracket Right.stl
  • 1x Fuselage.stl

The 3D files should be printed with 100% infill, except the Fuselage with ca. 70% infill.

I highly recommend to print all the left parts in one batch, assemble that wing-half and print the right parts then, to not mix them up by accident.

Additional Information

Daniel, the original designer of the Wing, mentioned, that he used (ca.) 2-2.5mm balsawood for the ribs.
In the original CAD Model he set them to be .7mm thick (certainly too thin).
He also mentioned, the A and G rib were a little to weak after covering the wing and bent.
I would recommend to use 2-3mm Plywood for those ribs.

The control surfaces are currently not included, but he said they were around 25mm long, using 2 or 2.5mm balsawood, but recommends making them longer (as also mentioned in the video). Also not included are the landing skids. He made them by hand from carbon using a dremel.

He as well said he had to modify the fuselage with a dremel to make it fit.
Once I have the time to build the wing myself I will modify it to make it fit right off the printer.

Also, a disclaimer from him is to "keep in mind that I just pulled this design out of thin air. By no means is it well thought out."

Build Info

The PDF file contains the ribs in vectorgraphics format and has a page size of DIN A3.
If printed in this size it can be glued to Balsawood and the ribs cut out, they are in ratio 1:1, just like the carbon spars.
It may also be possible to laser cut the ribs using inkscape and a few other programs to translate the vectorgraphic into code for a laser cutter.

Parts needed:
Carbon Rods (round):

  • 2 with 5mm Diameter, ca. 475mm Length
  • 2 with 3mm Diameter, ca. 460mm Length
  • 1 with 5mm Diameter, ca. 200mm Length

Trailing Edge (Balsa 15° Triangle):

  • 2 of 8.5mm Height, 29mm Depth, ca. 430mm Length

Balsawood:

  • 1-2 Sheets 1000x100x2mm (may have to be 2.5mm)

Plywood:

  • 1 Sheet 1000x100x2mm (may have to be 3mm)

Once I built the wing myself I will update the parts and plan to be better, as well as add some better instructions.
I'm grateful for comments with tips on building, if someone built the wing.
Also feel free to ask any questions regarding this.

Skip to 0:41 for this same flying wing.

In an effort to create more realism for my model railroad, I've created an interior floor plan for Walther's Lancaster Farmhouse, a picture of which has been included. The fireplace/chimney is open to allow for LED conduits, and the base of the kit is open to allow for resistors and general wiring.

description.text:
This is an 99% Isopropyl rocket engine designed as a project to practice for my rocket propulsion course in my Masters program.

Still needs to be refined but this is the current set up.

I use a high-voltage converter to ignite the fuel in the chamber by soldering the leads to two small nails inserted into the rear chamber cover.

A cap size of fuel is then poured into the chamber via the nozzle and sloshed around to create the proper vapour content in the chamber.

Then with the use of a switch ignite the fuel and enjoy!

Note* Be careful and be responsible and flammable materials are dangerous... By downloading this project you agree that you are responsible for all outcomes and no liability is left with the creator of this project.

title: Geeetech Prusa i3 Pro B Z-Axis Wobble Fix

description.text: I know there are loads of mods available to fix the Geeetech Prusa i3 Pro B wobbly Z-Axis but I prefer to design and print my own so I thought I would share my design. I have designed a replacement i3-08 top plate with an oversized hole for the M8 threaded rod to allow it to move. If the rod is bent and the rod is not free to move at the top all the movement will happen in the middle which causes the wobble on your printed pieces. I have also designed a piece to isolate the M8 brass nut from the X-Axis carriage so the M8 rod is not directly connected to the carriage and any deviation is not transferred to the print. Please not the picture of the replacement i3-08 is of an older design and it has since been modified.

description.text:
3D printed PVA parts to be used for molding a swirling unit, creating Vortex water. To restructure the water molecules and thus vitalizing the water? Is it actually working? I don't know but there´s lots of info out there claiming so. I designed this molded nozzle to raise the awareness for our urgent need for pure water on this planet. If this design works... great fun! If you start thinking about how you can contribute in some way... OUTSTANDING :-)

This design is based on https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:894682 (see included videos) but I did not yet test this molded version in real life, will you beat me to it?

The idea is to print the body and hose connector in PVA (PVA will dissolve in water thus creating the cavity after molding), perhaps it´s needed to spray paint the parts before molding in concrete due to the high water content. I guess you could mold with different materials like plastic etc but why not include this design (or several of them) in your concrete garden pond project?
Different hose connectors will be added when demanded, now 13mm(1/2"), 19mm(3/4") and 25,4mm(1") hose connectors are included.
Press-fit the hose connector into the body (use outer shell if wanted), add the hose, mold it all together and then dissolve the PVA... You could use some hobby clay or something to make the transition from the hose connector to the body smoother.
In the top you can find holes to be used for screwing it onto a plank or board (fixation during molding) or in the shell part.
The center hole is only a vent to make it easier to mold when not using the shell, you can brake off the pin created after molding.

author: Palmiga

title: Ikea Lack Table Stacking Drill Guide

description.text:
I wanted to stack some Ikea Lack tables. There are plenty of brackets, but they all take hours to print, so I decided to print 4 that would lift one set of table up. But the rest I decided to drill 1/2" holes for dowels and glue them in the table tops. The legs just drill through and the protruding part of the dowel holds them in place. The dowels swell with glue so no need to drill smaller holes.

I used one table just for the top to make a base. That was easy to drill the holes since you could just go through the back. In retrospect, I should have done all the drilling ahead of time. But I'd already put the tables together in anticipation of printing brackets. Yes, I could have taken them apart, but I didn't want to.

Drilling the legs is easy since you can use a ruler to find the center (draw an X from corner to opposite corner). But the table tops with the legs are hard to do. So I created this drill template which works for the tops or the legs.

The pilot hole is small, so the idea is you just get the drill point in there and make a mark, then remove the guide and finish the hole. You'll tear up the guide, but it is a few pennies worth of plastic and you can make more.

The legs are nominally 50.5mm square but there is quite a variation, so your mileage may vary. I went ahead and made this a customizer, but mostly just out of habit.

This was printed on my 5 year-old Printrbot Plus which has been modified more than the ship of Theseus.

The brackets in the finished product picture are these: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2002785 -- I did put two screws in the each of the back ones and cracked one. Some glue sort of fixed it. It is ugly but out of sight. But the others look great and work well.

title: Bowden-friendly Filament Guide for Ikea Lack

description.text:
This is a Filament guide designed for a bowden extruder mounted on an Ikea Lack table. This was specifically designed to go with the Bowden mount found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2137423

The flat sides of the lip are designed to nest inside the bottom of the mount, just where the bowden attachment is, while the 'wings' give it extra grip on the sides. The dip in the center of the filament guide allows for the bowden attachment on the stepper motor to sit just below the surface of the table and into the guide, for a flat, clean install. The center hole is 5mm - enough room to pass a PTFE tube.

The total dimensions are 18mm, but I use a 20mm hole through the table to allow a slight bit of play for the mount.

I have considered adding a bottom cover to make it super clean top and bottom, but it works well enough for now. Let me know if you'd like to see a bottom cover for this design.

description.text:
Two versions of indicator rings for miniatures on 30mm bases. I am using them for Kingdom Death: Monster miniatures.

I couldn't easily find anything on Thingiverse and this is loosely based on indicator rings that I have seen elsewhere (CMON games, Etsy). I do not have rings from either of these sources to compare against (but the Etsy ones look pretty sweet, character designation rings).

I have included a tight and a loose version.

The tight version will stay on the mini when you lift it up, but will scratch the paint along the edge of the base. I found it difficult to take off, and don't recommend it. Someone might find it handy though.

The loose version is what I am use. It doesn't stay on when you lift the mini up, easy to swap between uses and shouldn't be tight enough to scratch the paint on the edge of the base.

description.text:
Update 1/19/18: I am slowly adding each tray cut into 4 pieces (UL, LL, UR, LR). Only Tray 1, 2, 3 needed to be cut into four's for smaller printers.

Update 1/18/18: To eliminate any confusion, I am removing the layer files. I would recommend printing the Tray Insert_Tray files if you have a big enough bed or the L&R versions which fit the Prusa bed or any bed within that size.

Updated 1/13/18: Added the missing ledges on the character tray (Tray 5) that keeps the action cards elevated from the items and modifier deck.

Update 1/12/18: I uploaded Tray 1 L & R again because they didn't seem to process correctly. I have Tray 3 (PLA) and 4 (PETG) printed and pictures uploaded. I am just testing which filament works better for Trays as well as tolerances between filaments.

Update 1/4/18: Test print went well. I posted a picture of tray 2 in beige/purple. It is a tight fit, so make sure your printer is calibrated. I would recommend a top layer of 6 with 15% infill to get a clean top surface.

Update 1/2/18: Rebuilt the rest of the inserts and split them. They should print fine now.

Update 1/1/18: Tray 2 Rebuilt and Split.

Update 1/1/18: I was hoping these didn't needed to be redone for printing but @steellynx was right, I will have to redo these because its not printing correctly.

The initial files are converted from Skjalm (@steellynx) svg files he posted on facebook. The original design came from Martijn on facebook.

Most of the pieces will not fit most printers, so I will work on getting them cut up to fit at least for a Prusa

author: boyfriend

title: Metal Defender Voltron Wing Joint Fix

description.text:
The Target Exclusive Metal Defender Voltron is a great 8 inch, combinable Voltron with a few problems that can be fixed, depending on your mod skills.

One problem is that they skimped on a joint at the back of the wings that would allow the wings to face forward in Voltron mode. This is nearly false advertisement as the back of the box clearly has them facing this way.

Well, in about 15 minutes or so, you can have two joints that you can use to get the direction you desire. Just plug the wings into the holes in the joints, then push the printed part into where the wing plug should go.

I printed mine at 0.3mm and 20% infill, though I don't believe the infill matters much. It should print without supports. Once done, use a knife to scrape off the support block. If for some reason you scrape a bit too much off, one old toy fixer trick is to get some clear nail polish and brush a bit of it on the printed plug. Let it dry, and this should add the tiny amount of thickness you need to get a friction fit. This technique works for a large number of toys that have loose joints. Just make sure it dries before reinserting it.

comments.text: Hello.  Can you show a photo from the back of Voltron to see how these joints work?
comments.author: h82blat

comments.text: Sure, I can later tonight or this weekend.  But it is pretty simple.  You push the plug into the hole in the back that the wings would normally go into, then you push the wings into the circle/ring/hole that the printed piece has.  It's all friction fit, so then things should just stay in place.  It's not any complex mechanical mechanism.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
My hallway had an ancient copper-leaded glass "thing" for a light, I could no longer abide.
I modeled this replacement in Maya, measures just over 9.5" tall and across.

Printer:

Tevo Little Monster

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

200 micron

Notes:

I designed these walls to have thicknesses so that if you print with two shells at .48mm thick (.4mm nozzle 20% over-width), and no infill, you should get walls exactly 4 shells thick, giving a nice sturdy print. Took me 9.5 hours total print time.

Programmed two pauses so I could swap the matte gray PLA for transparent, and back again.
I would not use an incandescent bulb in this, the heat would probably end up being too much for the filament.

"Westinghouse Lighting Glass Shade Holder Kit, 3-1/4 Inch, 60 watt, Antique Brass"

For the light, I installed a GE soft white (2700k) 75w (replacement, 13w actual) LED bulb.

description.text:
A small experiment with foils to evaluate the feasibility of a flying boat with U shaped hydrofoils. This is a pure Fablab creation we started to have the idea to test this with Ricardo at 20h00 one evening @ the Artilect Fablab in Toulouse and at midnight all the part where designed & cut ready for assembly. The end idea could be to modify a hobbiecat or similar boat. But for now it is to have fun with the understanding of hydrofoils. Concept to demonstrate:
  • U shaped foil which have to following interesting advantages:
    • Reduced induced drag due to the presence of sidewalls
    • No stress concentration a the root of the wing requiring costly carbon fibers
    • Connected to the bot by a pivot axis allowing easy angle of attack control and to put the foil out of water for ditching.
    • Things not included in this design:
  • A decent hull
  • lateral control & stability
  • Pitch & altitude control & stability
  • Hydrofoil polar calculation
    • Hydrofoil design:
  • Chord widith 74mm
  • Speed 5kph -> 1.4m/s
  • Water kinematic viscosity @ 10degC = 1.267E-6m^2/s
  • Reynolds (in water) Re = 8.0X10^4
  • Lifting surface 0.03m^2
  • Initial idea was to use an Eppler 818 profile it is good at those low Reynolds numbers. More details can be found there http://airfoiltools.com/airfoil/details?airfoil=e818-il
  • However making such a small profile with styrofoam was an issue.
  • Since at those very low reynolds a flat plate works well. a 1 mm plastic plate was used with some camber.
    • First test:
  • Very crude just pulled by a truing at the end of a stick on the local river
  • She managed to take off at fast walking pace even loaded up to 3.5kg
  • The hull shape is extremely crude & the bow create an incidence effect to the front foil requiring a bit more incidence to take off.
    • What is next:
  • Upgrade the prototype to have a better hull shape
  • Integrate lateral and vertical control
  • integrate a propulsion system making similar effort as sails.
  • generate a polar for the foils.
    • Pictures Courtesy of Ricardo.

Very simple build with laser cut 3mm plywood Assembly with a lot of hot glue. Pitch adjustment through an adjusting screw guided by a long nut fixed to the hull with more hot glue. The wing part of the foil in in 1mm plastic foil.
initial idea for the wing was a profile cut in stirofoam with hot wire but it was not practical for such a small shape. and we found out that at these extremely low Reynolds just a curved flat plate was perfect.

description.text: dress2-9

This is a gear bearing or planetary gear that I designed with SolidEdge ST8.
The gears have an involute arrow gearing.
The ring gear has 21 teeth, the planet gears and the sun gear have 7 teeth.

There are two different sizes of the gearbearing, a small and a large version.
The large version was my initial design with a ring diameter of 131.3mm(1.17") and a height of 15mm(0.59").
The small version is exactly the same design just skaled smaller in order to print it also in smaller sizes. It has a ring diameter of 53mm(2.09") and a height of 10mm(0.39").

The large one is printable from 60%(approximately 80mm(3.15")) upwards, on my printer.

I like to use these kind of gear bearings for my filament holder, to make sure the printer can easily pull filament of the spool.

Simple Christmas Ornament

This simple Christmas ornament is a good addition to any maker's tree for the holidays. It prints fast and well on most printers making it also wonderful for that one person you know you forgot to get a present. If you want, download either the version with the heart, hyphen, or nothing depending on who you want to give it to. The ones with the heart and hyphen leave room for you to put your name (text size may be smaller than shown in the example one for names with more than six letters).

Versions

Current Version: 1.0

Future Versions

In future versions (likely 1.1) the background of the ornament will get a better design. An easy to edit customize-able version (likely 1.2) will be added to allow people to more easily add their name after the heart under where it says "Merry Christmas" for a more personal delivery to friends and family. In a soon update (likely 1.2) videos will be added.

Recommended Settings

Settings in order from: Cura
If you want to download Cura you can get it from the Ultimaker website HERE

Layer Height: 0.06 (mm)
Wall Thickness: 0.06 (mm)
Top/Bottom Thickness: 0.06 (mm)

Infill Density: 100 (%)
Gradual Infill Steps: 0

Printing Temperature: Varies based on material
Build Plate Temperature: Varies based on material
(Filament) Diameter: 1.75 (mm)
Flow: 100 (%)
Enable Retraction: Enabled (Click the box until a check mark appears)

Print Speed: 20 (mm/s)
Travel Speed: 60 (mm/s)

Enable Print Cooling: Enabled (Click the box until a check mark appears)

Generate Support: Enabled (Click the box until a check mark appears)
Support Placement: Everywhere (Click the drop-down arrow and select)
Build Plate Adhesion Type: Select Any (Not Needed)
Print Sequence: Select Any (It's only one piece)

*Please Note The settings above will not be in the same order for all software. As well, this is not sponsored by Ultimaker, it is just my personal preference to use because it is powerful and free.
NGSS CCSS
This is a great simple and quick to print ornament that can be given to a friend or family member as a way to say Merry Christmas in a fun and unique way.
Activity's Goal The goal of the activity is to provide a nice gift with a small way to customize it with their name. This is a good introduction into text in cad software.

What You Will Need While the ornament will hang on a tree with just the loop at the top, it is recommended that you attach one of the following to it:
- A Paperclip
- 3 Inch String (~7-8 cm)
- Rubberband

description.text:
Recently I realized that I was missing playing music from tapes. Not because of sound quality but because of that feeling of 80's :-)
So I purchased preowned tape desk and few cassettes.
To have even better visual experience I've designed reel-to-reel cassette upgrade.
It is far from professional reel-to-reel cassettes but it does not cost fortune and it looks pretty good.
Disadvantage is that you need to cut off almost half od 90 min cassette tape so you end up with ~50 minutes. But it is not a problem for me.

Reels are 0.2 mm thin so it is good to have calibrated bed.
I am using capton tape for good adhesion even in low bed temperatures and for glossy finish of bottom layer.
I used PLA for printing and 0.3 mm nozzle.

Video is here: https://youtu.be/oTubU1VG-n0
Instructions are attached.

This is still work in progress - currently there are two types of design of inner supporting structure. The first one is easier to remove, the second one adds better support for inner cylinder.

title: RPG Tokens with Numbers and Skulls

description.text:
I wanted some tokens I could use for playing pen and paper games for random NPCs and monsters without having to print a new model for anything I made. These are meant to be little generic tokens for medium sized creatures. There is a number on one side to help keep track of which token is which NPC and a skull on the other side you can flip to if the NPC dies.

The number side has little circles to reduce the distance for bridging, but even then that surface probably wont print as clean as around the skull. Need more numbers? I recommend printing this set in multiple colors as needed. For instance you can have a red 1 and a green 1.

I stole the face off a skull by YahooJAPAN so to give credit, I marked it as a remix of that despite it being a very different project.

I designed this using TinkerCad and 3D Builder. Hope you enjoy my work!

print_settings.Notes:: Printed in PLA @ 195C with a bed temperature of 60C.  It's a pretty big print, so make sure the bed is hot enough to ensure that it sticks properly during printing

description.text:
I was trying to print a lot of things on my CR-10S with NinjaFlex and got tired of it binding in the long bowden tube. Even on a normal filament I occasionally got bad prints because the tube had pushed out of the extruder for some reason. The mechanics of the Creality extruder/bowden assembly seem like a pretty poor design to me.

So I started to design a direct drive system to move the extruder stepper above the hot end and limit my bowden tub to less than an inch. Though I have pretty much replaced all of the printer's original extruder and hot end parts, I wanted this to generally reuse all of the parts that came with my printer when I bought it. The resulting thing comes in two parts:

  1. The main motor plate that is sandwiched between the existing carriage plate and the hot end. This also holds the stepper motor and extruder parts and includes a harness for the hot end cables. (see photos)

  2. A replacement plate for the X-axis limit switch. This is necessary due to the added thickness of the direct drive plate so it can make contact with the switch.

Printer:

Creality CR-10S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Printed in PLA @ 195C with a bed temperature of 60C. It's a pretty big print, so make sure the bed is hot enough to ensure that it sticks properly during printing

• Installation should be straightforward (see photos). The direct drive stepper plate is held by the existing hot end and fan shroud bolts. Make sure to add a suitably sized piece of bowden tube between the extruder and and hot end - the length of this will vary depending on the parts chosen.

  • I have replaced the original screws with better ones and mine are probably longer than the original screws that held the fan shroud and hot end. You may need to do the same - they are all M3 screws if you didn't already know

  • My extruder is from MacEwen3D (https://macewen3d.com/products/mk8-extruder-aluminum-drive-feed-for-cr-10-cr-10-s4-and-cr-10-s5) and works amazingly well. The original extruder should work as well however.

  • My hot end is from Micro Swiss (https://store.micro-swiss.com/collections/creality-cr-10/products/300-c-flexible-friendly-hotend-kit-for-cr-10-printers) however the original hot end should work without any issues

  • Don't worry about the added weight of the stepper motor. It sits right above the x-axis rail and should not pull the carriage off-balance. Stepper vibration isn't a measurable factor while printing.

  • Make sure the wire for the stepper motor is long enough to reach across the bed. In my case it was just long enough but depending on Creality's assembly accuracy yours may be shorter and may require an extension.
I built this from scratch using Fusion 360 (thank-you Autodesk!) and sliced it with Simplify 3D. Total implementation time, including design and printing many prototypes was about 30 hours.

comments.text: One of the reasons the plate sticks out to the left more is so it comes into contact with the X-axis switch a bit earlier, thereby making enough room to accommodate the stepper, and as you've noted, this does rob a few millimetres from the x-axis.  Not much that can be done about that unfortunately, unless the stepper motor is flipped to the front of the plate, but that would require a bit more thought.
comments.author: MrJelle

comments.text: Thanks in advance! If you want to just add a specific version to your own thing upload, that'd of course be fine by me. Once my current print (testing flexible filament at long last now that the distance between extruder and hot end is muuuch shorter!) finishes, I'll figure out exactly how much room I have left between stepper motor and left Z-tower (to see how much shorter the plate can be made on the left), and see if I have any idea about how to handle the right side... For now, I've got 270mm of X-axis reach left by cutting some off the right, but that's with the X home placed about 20mm too far to the right, so, ultimately... This should be about 10mm of loss on the X axis, which I'm willing to accept until I can get a pancake stepper that won't hit either tower in any case!

Project Asbtract: Among the last frontiers of astronomy are the polarizationmeasurements of x and gamma rays, emitted from phenomena as diverse as gamma ray bursts, pulsars, and active galactic nuclei. Our payload consists of a 4x4 pixel CdTe prototype developed to characterize background radiation in the 20 - 100 keV energy range. Measuring double events is essential in determining Compton photons' new direction and therefore the polarization direction. The SSGX payload features both the CACTus detection unit which previously launched from Italy in 2002 (recording single events), and an innovative electronic data collection system designed by American River College, Sacramento Ca Physics and Astronomy Club. The Data Acquisition/Integrated Storage Interface (DAISI) is responsible for sampling detector analog voltages, supplying required voltages, monitoring system operation, regulating electronics temperature, responding to remote communication, and the continuous recording of acquired data as well as system status to permanent storage. It is crucial to develop reliable calibration data for future instruments, this project's goal is to obtain, for the first time, a fine measurement of all background components(single, double, and multiple events) that can deteriorate a gamma ray polarimeter response in space.
NGSS

Detector Payload Previous Flight Experience Our Stratospheric Spectropolarimeter Gamma-X (SSGX) payload is based on the detection capacities of the Compact Array of Cadmium Telluride Micro Spectrometers (CACTμS), [22]. During a twelve-hour balloon flight, launched from Sicily, Italy, in 2002, the CACTμS instrument collected data exclusively for single events’ background. We now propose to explore the implementation of coincidence logic for double and multiple events. Double events (two hits within different pixels, the first interaction being a Compton) are essential in determining Compton photons' new direction and therefore the polarization direction.
The CACTμS instrument includes the primary detector housing (CdTe detectors) with associated front-end electronics (voltage supplies, temperature sensors, Charge Sensitive Preamps/CSPs With respect to other former CACTμS’ electronics subsystems, our new SSGX payload represents a major upgrading with substantial downsizing in both weight and dimensions of the service electronics. The image below shows the large dimensions of CACTμS’ subsystems that included the analog front end electronics (AFEE) box, the Pulse Code Modulation Unit (PCM), the scientific Data Handling System (DHS) with Analogue to Digital Conversion (ADC) and digital control electronics, and the Telecommand/Telemetry unit. These would easily occupy all of the space allotted for the four large payloads as accommodated by HASP.

Payload Subsystem DAISI DAISI (Data Acquisition/Integrated Storage Interface) is an electronics platform developed by the American River College Physics & Astronomy Club, designed to collect sensor data from multiple sources, monitor and regulate system functionality, and record collected data to an SD card. The primary data collected consists of analog voltage levels from the array of eight CdTe strips for the purpose of recording x-ray and γ-ray events. Additional data collected includes system voltage levels, detector and electronics temperatures, and system status such as error states. This data is also saved in real time to an SD card for post-flight evaluation, and instantaneous readings of all data may also be queried utilizing an RS-232 interface. The RS-232 interface is further capable of receiving commands to override and adjust automatic functionality. Finally, through monitoring of the electronics temperature, onboard logic can respond by activating resistive heating elements for purposes of thermal regulation, ensuring that all components remain within appropriate thermal tolerances.
High Altitude Ballon Currently seeking payload opportunities for experiment.

title: Schacht Bulky Bobbin for faster whorls in double drive

description.text: This bobbin is for those with Schacht wheels that can utilise double drive, and for those spinners who want to use the bulky flyer to spin and ply large amounts of finer yarn using the fast and high speed whorls. The ends are interchangeable, as they screw onto the core. The fast bobbin end will work with the fast whorl, the hi-speed end will work with the high speed whorl, and the silly speed end should enable double drive plying with the high speed whorl. I've also added a plain end, which doesn't have a whorl but does have a groove for use with tensioned Lazy Kates, which you can put on the orifice end of the bobbin if you so wish. Finally there are orifice reducers...... 5 mm, 10 mm and 15 mm orifices depending on how fine you are trying to spin

This may need a bit of sanding down, particularly the hole for the flyer shaft, and the edges of the threads. The flyer shaft does fit, but I found the base of the core that had been on the platform needed a bit of smoothing off before it would go, as the fit is snug. It also takes a bit of work to get the core to thread onto the ends the first time, again this can be fixed with a gentle sanding. I used a good quality fabric backed medium and very fine sandpaper.

The orifice reducer may be a little loose, but I think making it any bigger will mean it could be a bit too tight. I put a narrow strip of electrical tape around the end nearest the flange, which helped it sit more firmly

I used the measurements of Schacht bobbins, measuring the whorl diameter of the fast and high speed bobbin ends with fine string, then calculating the diameter. The whorls have been put onto a bulky bobbin sized end.

I found lots of standard T-Plug caps on TI. But not for the Amass T-Plugs. There you are.

Many z-switch holder are mounted to the z-axis motor holder which in my book is nonsense. With a z-switch holder mounted to the frame of the printer you can disassemble the z-axis and won't have to recalibrate the z-position afterwards everytime.

Made it by using a caliper, Solidworks 2013 and just a little bit of savvy... It's work in progress. I haven't had the time yet to actually test it on my real printer. It fits over the profile. That's all I can say so far. But I hope that I'll be able to see if the switch itself is positioned correctly (along the x-axis, kind of). It looks good but I won't say it fits before I've actually tried it by myself. //edit 01:02am: Alright, it's fine. Fits like a glove. Might be that you'll have to rotate it to print it like I'd recommend: with the profile contour along the z-axis and the stop-switch mount upwards (like hopefully in the newly uploaded STL).

title: Portable, Compact Dice Tower/Case (magnetic)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Compact three-piece dice tower and tray that doubles as a dice box when not in use. N48 strength cube magnets hold the sides together, and hold the tower to the tray when in use, and keep the three pieces together snugly when stored.

In storage mode, dice larger than 13mm are trapped and can't shake out. Stores approximately 25 dice, depending on sizes and shapes.

Roll tested with 14, 15 and 16mm d6 dice and handfuls of other standard sized dice (d4, d8, d10/100, d12, d20).

See Post-Printing instructions for help with aligning the magnets correctly.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.3mm

Infill:

20%

Inserting the Magnets and Ensuring Correct Polarity

Holes are sized for 3/16" cube magnets (such as https://totalelement.com/collections/cube-magnets/products/totalelement-64-neodymium-magnets-3-16-inch-cube-n48). You will need twenty (20) magnets.

Files were created with .4mm tolerance, which for my printer results in the magnets press-fitting pretty snugly all around and just a hair below the surface. However, a bit of epoxy or CA glue goes a long way to ensuring they stay put, especially in the one magnet at the bottom of each side that does not have four sides of support.

Left and Right Sides
First, insert 5 magnets into the right side.

Then, one at a time, place a second magnet onto one of the magnets you just inserted, so that their polarities align (see picture). Align the appropriate hole on the left side with the free magnet and press it down to insert the magnet into the left side. Do this for all five magnets. When done, the two sides should snap together well, with none of the magnets repelling each other.

Tray and Storage Side
Decide whether you want the dice to be stored to the left or right. Repeat the process above, aligning the four corners on the open/top side of the tray to the chosen left or right side. When done, the tray should snap together with the chosen side.

Tray and Empty Side
Repeat the process a third time, aligning the four corners on the bottom side of the tray with the remaining left or right side. When done, all three pieces should snap together, left and right sides with the tray in the middle.

NOTE: The end of the tray with the small support ledge and holes in the middle for two magnets should be aligned with the top of the dice tower sides, so that its magnets don't conflict with the magnets in the bottoms of the two sides.

Tower Support Ledge
Finally, put the left and right sides together, and place two magnets on the bottom so that their polarities align with the magnets you inserted there earlier. Position the tower over the tray so that these two magnets align with the two-magnet hole in middle of one end of the tray, and press down to insert them. When done, these magnets should serve to hold the tower on the tray while in use.

title: Leopold - smooth algebraic surface
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Leopold, a smooth algebraic surface of degree six. This is the set of real points for which 

1000*x^2*y^2*z^2+3*x^2+3*y^2+z^2-1 = 0.

No singularities! Smooth everywhere!

I have provided these files:

  • leopold_fixed.stl -- has the normal vectors fixed.
  • leopold_raw.stl -- raw triangulation coming from Bertini_real. Since the program works in arbitrary dimensions, I make no effort to control normals from it -- they don't exist for 4- and higher-dimensional surfaces, but instead a tangent space which is not immediately useful for 3d printing. The raw versions are not directly suitable for 3d printing.
  • input -- the Bertini_real input file used to compute it.

This surface was sampled before I implemented cyclenumber > 1 sampling, so the surface is undersampled near critical points and singularities.

Computed with a Numerical Algebraic Geometry program I wrote, called Bertini_real and printed as part of my long-term project to reproduce Herwig Hauser's gallery of algebraic surface ray-traces in my own gallery of 3d prints. The ACM ToMS algorithm number is 976; the major published paper is DOI 10.1145/3056528 with several others preceding. Bertini_real implements the implicit function theorem for algebraic surfaces and curves in any (reasonable) number of variables.

These surfaces are generally challenging to print. Rotate, and use careful support. I use Simplify3D for the manual support placement feature. These surfaces are also very tiny in scale (arbitrary units and math and all) so require significant upsizing.

See also, my Thingiverse collection of algebraic surfaces.

This is a laser cuttable insert for the game Gloomhaven (2nd print edition) with room for all the game component inside the original box.
EDIT: someone informed me that he could fit all the cards with sleeves in the bottom tray :-)
To cut this, start by engraving/tracing the green lines (i.e. wall guides and texts) then cut the yellow lines (internal holes) and finally the black lines.
The attached images should show how to pack everything in the trays and place them in the Gloomhaven box.

There are two sets of SVG files:

  • Layer 1 to Layer 5 - individual trays/layers in separate files
  • Layers 1+2 and 3+4+5 - rearranged trays/layers for cutting on two 600x800mm sheets.

Note that the SVG files use millimeters as the base unit. Please make sure you import them with the correct settings or the scale will be wrong.

Paul Doronila converted this to a 3D print version
SquishyWizard kindly supplied CorelDraw versions of the insert both with and without the text layer. For faster cutting, use the one without the texts.

comments.author: steellynx

comments.text:
My two cents is that it's probably easier/better to redo everything more or less from scratch rather than trying to modify the files. This is mainly because you will need to modify all the "teeth" that holds the walls together to match the exact thickness of your board, but also because the height of the trays will change slightly so you'll also need to adjust the wall heights accordingly.
Use the basic layout of the trays as the basis for an imperial measurement insert, but remember to check that there is still physical room for the cards, preferably with sleeves. As it is now the party tray (tray 5 with the angled cut-outs) is a really tight fit for the sleeved action cards, so you'll want to double check that there's still room. Or you can be creative and engrave the walls to be around ½mm or so thinner at the top to give that little bit extra space for the sleeves ;-)
Whichever way you go I hope you have fun doing it and end up with a well-working insert.

Just a little Christmas Ornament. Easy to print. ;)

With too many gadgets come too many cables, so to keep them in place I've designed molds to produce simple cable tidies for a number of different diameter wires.

Once the mold is printed and cleaned, dust it with talcum powder lightly on the inside making sure all areas are covered, then fill the mold carefully with household/builders silicone taking care not to trap any air, fill to the top and smooth off. Allow to cure for at least a few days then remove carefully from mold.

I designed it for use with double sided sticky tabs of 20mm dia or square, so once its out of the mold either use double sided tape/tabs or hook & eye spots and place where needed, the cables should push in and out without too much resistance but be held neatly.
There are molds for cables of upto 4mm, 5mm, 6mm, 7mm, and 10mm.

I made them all the same height so that different sizes would match if used in a row.
4mm should take the majority of gadget charging cables, 7mm sat/tv and with the rest I hope to have covered most needs.

title: FT Gremlin Frame by Andres Lu

description.text:
IT’S ALL ABOUT THE FUN!

Flite Test created a brushless micro quad that’s all about the fun and creative experience. That’s why they designed the Gremlin to be just as fun to build as it is to fly. It’s a swappable style design that can be easily modified to express your own creativity.

Flite Test sells Gremlin frames made from 3/32 (.094) inch thick Delrin or Carbon. The frames are incredibly durable and work great for indoor and outdoor flying, making the Gremlin an affordable option for those learning to fly quads and for seasoned pilots as well. Now you can print your own frames using the same shape files used by Flite Test to cut the delrin and carbon frames.

We’ll be releasing more frame designs in the future as well as free plans to go along with them. And in the swappable spirit, we want to see what YOU create! Share your ideas for Gremlin frames on our YouTube channel, Facebook page or in an article, and it could become a Gremlin community release on the Flite Test Store!

UPDATE: 1/28/2018 - Added feature to prevent mid-point deflection when using the middle zip-tie mount option. This new design supercedes the original.

I developed these leg extensions for my DJI Phantom 3 to help with a drop mechanism (coming soon :) ). They provide ~135mm lift (depending on leg positioning) and can be used to provide extra ground clearance for takeoff/landing with payloads or when landing in tall, grassy areas without affecting the gimbal.

Print two of these extensions and attach using one or more zip ties (three zip tie locations are provided for each extension). Then, position/shape each leg using hot air from a heat gun or hot air rework station (see details below).

I designed this for a Phantom 3. But, it may also fit a Phantom 1, 2, or 4. The payload capacity for a Phantom 3 is just over 2 pounds (907 grams). So far, I have used these extensions with the applications shown:

  • Water Balloon drop mechanism - development completed, just finalizing files before publishing. The water balloon shown weighs about 1/2 pound. When dropped from 400 feet, it hits the ground going over 100 miles per hour and leaves a small crater.
  • Mantis Claw - www.thingiverse.com/thing:1659427.

MakerGear

MakerGear M2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3 mm

Infill:

50%

Shaping - Leg positioning

After attaching the extensions to your drone, flip the drone upside-down and gently shape the extensions using hot air from a heat gun. In the pictures shown, hot air (set to 250C for PLA) from a soldering rework station was used to gently heat around the base of each extension leg until it was soft enough to tilt slightly into final position. Hold the leg in place until the plastic cools.

remixed_from.title: Anet A8 E3D Titan Aero Mount & Fan Duct

title: Anet A8 Titan Aero Mount v2 w/ inductive sensor mount

description.text:
Tips are definitely welcome, and Amazon links below are affiliate links. I appreciate your support!
 

Description

New version of the titan aero mount I had made (old mount)

X axis has 250mm+ range of motion with this upgrade, capable of reaching the entire bed. Attached pictures show the extruder's reach.
 

New Features

  • Increased rigidity across all dimensions
  • Size allowance for 5mm vibration damper (Amazon)
  • (Optional) Mount for "extra big-ass" (8mm) inductive sensor (Amazon)
  • Belt holder redesign, could even be replaced with different belt holder if desired (fits standard A8 mount)
  • Fan mount removed, as many superior options are now available that mount directly onto the Aero heatsink
  • Can be mirrored (in your slicer settings)
     

Required Hardware

Some or all of the following can be salvaged from the original Anet A8 gantry
12- M4x8mm bolts (or longer) for mounting to bearings
2- M3x18mm bolts (or longer) for attaching belt gripper
2- M3 nut for attaching belt gripper
(optional) 3- M3x40mm bolts for extruder motor with damper

Installation Notes

The extruder motor should slide in somewhat diagonally into the hole. I've shortened the right end vertical wall significantly to accommodate this, eliminating the need for the slot in the top of the motor mount wall.

If you use the mirrored setup, I make no guarantees to the usefulness of the sensor mount, but I'd love to hear any feedback from someone who does and how well it worked out.
 

Recommended Addons

Part fan adapter from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2567051

Laminar flow fan plate (thing:432630) - this keeps the extruder fan from blowing over the nozzle and increases fan efficiency

I completely love this 40mm fan (Amazon) - it blows a fat load of air while being completely silent at 5v. It's really a big upgrade over the fan provided with the Aero. I'm not sponsored, just a happy customer.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm layer height / 0.4mm nozzle

Infill:

40-80%

Notes:

There are built-in thin supports for the sensor mount, as well as a version that would require supports to be made by the slicer instead. Either version will result in the same finished product, print whatever you're comfortable with.

Nozzle size:
The built-in sensor supports are designed for a 0.4mm nozzle, so that'd be my recommendation.

Material Recommendation:
Whatever is as rigid as possible. This probably means PLA for most people, preferably a high temp variant as they have even higher rigidity. Heat resistance is not a concern for this part, so PLA will be just fine for the long term.

description.text:
Do you have a 3D systems cube that has soul crushing print failures?

Often the cause for print failures is old and brittle 3DS filament that breaks in the feed path when being fed into the top nozzle. The default 3DS system puts a lot flexing stress on the filament and the feed tubing is fragile usually leading to clogs and print failures.

This is a "bowden" PTFE tube assembly replacement that is intended to limit the amount of flex and reduce friction on the filament as it is fed into the extruder. With the help of the 3DS filament "hack" non 3DS filament can also be used.

http://www.print3dforum.com/showthread.php/900-Cube3-Filament-*SOFTWARE*-Hack-is-here!!!

The "HubCap" can be used without the "HubClip" by the installed magnets. The "HubClip" will clip in-place to add extra security, is designed to help channel the stepper cooling fan air to the metal extruder housing and provides a filament feed guide. TO remove the Hubclip, simply pull straight off.

This "kit" consists of 4 separate 3D printed parts. It also uses several parts from the stock 3DS filament cartridge.

The additional parts needed are:

3DS Cube metal extruder housing, HOBB bearings and screws etc.
3DS Cube metal nozzle tip
3DS Cube nozzle spring
3DS Cube 3mm PTFE tub3
3DS Cube Filament Chip from cartridge housing.
PTFE Teflon tubing 2mm ID 4mm OD https://www.captubes.com/shop/#!/1-Meter-Low-Friction-Bowden-Tubing/p/82190682/category=23214267
2x M6 Pneumatic quick fittings. https://www.captubes.com/shop/#!/4-Pack-PC4-M6-Fittings/p/84203147/category=25823850
M6 thread tap (matching the pneumatic fittings you are using) https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B071VKZ2DC/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
2x 8mm wide 3mm thick Neodymium Disc Magnets https://www.homedepot.com/p/MASTER-MAGNETICS-0-3-in-x-0-11-in-Neodymium-Rare-Earth-Magnet-Discs-10-per-Pack-07045HD/202526363

WARNING:

The purpose of this was to get my cube printing again at 70nm without filament failure, the stock parts were simply not working at all.

However the fix has a few potentially frustrating aspects.

  1. The filament needs to be loaded by turning the hobb-gear with a screw driver. The filament tends to get curled by the gear so initially feeding filament past the extruder into the PTFE tube may take several tries. I found it best to have the filament cut at an angle to help the end slip past the small inner edge between the extruder and pneumatic quick fitting. Once loaded, I tend not to change the filament often.

  2. The "HubClip" is intended to be as simple as possible to print. The clip section that inserts into the cube printer can be fragile depending upon the material printed and settings used. I use ABS, as I found PLA to be less flexible. The clip can be hard to remove, but I simply pull it straight off or use a flat head screw diver to ply it loose on one side first.

  3. Be careful when installing and removing the printed head, it is best to wait until it has cooled off to make any adjustments. Polycarbonate is more resistent to heat compared to PLA and ABS.

Big thanks to the members on 3Dprintforum.com in particular

TommyDee, MegaloDon, bolsoncerrado, Mythandar, and ztoddman1

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 5

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.4 nozzle size, 200 microns for the Hubcap and HubClip.100nm for the Nozzle

Infill:

30% for the Hubcap and HubClip. 95% for the Nozzle

Notes:

The parts can likely be printed on a 3DS cube, I did all my test printing on Lulzbot Taz 5.

All the parts can be printed in PLA, PETG, ABS or PC. I have tested the hub with PLA and ABS and the nozzle with PLA and Polymaker PC Plus.

I highly recommend:
  1. Using Polymaker PC Plus (or regular Polycarbonate filament) for the print nozzle if you have prints lasting over and hour. The housing is close to the heater black and gets warm.
  2. Instead of PLA, print using PETG if possible.
  3. Using Simplify3D to prepare the file as the supports will be easy to remove.
  4. If using PLA/PETG/ABS, waiting of the nozzle to cool down before removing or changing filament, otherwise you risk head coming apart or deforming too much.

Step #1 Print Cleaup

Cleanup printed parts. The Nozzle is designed to print with a .4mm to .6mm thread clearance.

Step #2 Tapping

Bolt the 3DS metal housing together and tap the filament output end for the M6 Pneumatic quick fitting.

Step #3 Tapping

Tap the top of the nozzle housing for the M6 Pneumatic quick fitting.

Step #4 Pneumatic fitting adjustment

Enlarge ONE Pneumatic quick fitting tapped end using a 3mm or 7/64" drill bit, to make room for the stock 3mm 3DS PTFE tube.

Step #5 Cut 3mm PTFE tube

Cut a section of the 3mm 3DS PTFE tube to 38mm in length. This will be inserted into the metal nozzle tip (the tip needs to be is clean and clear or filament). The other end will fit into the Pneumatic quick fitting that was enlarged

Step #6 Cut 4mm PTFE tube

Cut the bowden PTFE Teflon tubing to about 455mm or 18" in length

Step #7 Assembly

Assemble the various parts, please refer to the photos for guidance.

Carefully remove the filament chip from the 3DS cartridge. I can be peeled off and its adhesive re-used to attach it to the HubCap

STL parts modeled in Modo using Mesh Fusion. Photos of install is using Capricorn XS Tubing instead of plain white PTFE tubing.

Hub installed with nozzle. The feed tubes should NOT be tucked into the printer housing. Side "HubCap" and "HubClip" with eSun filament loading into the bottom. Nozzle assembled, printed using Polymaker PC Plus. All the parts. HubCap and HubClip printed in "natural" Protoparadigm ABS filament. Nozzle top and bottom printed in white Polymaker PC Plus filament. Bottom of hubcap and hubclip w filament chip installed. Note the alignment of the chip. Top of nozzles installed. Extruder housing on HubCap with magnets glued in place. Inside hubcap w chip and housing installed. Tapped extruder housing w M6 fitting. Nozzle parts with fitting opening enlarged to ~3mm

title: X-Axis Stabilizer Blocks for Maker Select V2

description.text: It seemed to matter how tight I could get the set screws on my x-axis rods, there was still a lot of play there. The x-axis motor and idler mounts would "pigeon toe" towards each other when the belt was tightened even a little bit. My printer had a lot of vibration that I could not eliminate even after z-axis braces and other mods. So I designed these little blocks to help stabilize the x-axis rods and it has made a huge improvement in reducing vibration. I did have some collision with the blocks due to using the "Ultimate Wanhao i3 X Belt tensioner" so be aware of that and be sure to check all clearances and end stop switch. My printer has a .2mm over-extrusion error so the holes are 8.2mm for an exact fit. You need to print two for one side, then mirror and print two for the other. You also need 8 M3 screws 10mm-12mm long.

title: PETG Adhesion Test for CR-10
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
First Layer Improvement Thing.

Ok, this sure is a very simple thing, but while struggling with an adhesion problem on the first layer I thought maybe this is helpful for others, too.

It's an one layer flat square (50x50 mm).

The two photos of the thing show what my problem was while I was dialing in the config for my new CR-10 printing PETG from DasFilament.
(Added the screenshots of my final S3D config)


Update: 31.12.2017

Config screens corrected.
Just realized I uploaded the wrong config screens.
Don't use the previous config, especially not retraction and infill width. Chances are high they will clog your nozzle!



Maybe this G-Code snippets are helpful, too.

(Works on my CR-10 with clamps on front and back. Not tested with any other clamp position or machine!)

Starting Script:
M83 ; use relative distances for extrusion
G28 ; home axes
M203 Z20 E200 ; set max feedrate
M84 S0 ; disable stepper timeout
M104 S[extruder0_temperature];
M140 S[bed0_temperature];
G1 X0 Y50 Z20 F8000 ; go to front of the bed
M190 S[bed0_temperature];
M109 S[extruder0_temperature];
G92 E0 ; reset extrusion distance
G1 Z0.3 ; get ready to prime
G1 Y250 E25 F600 ; prime nozzle
G1 Z0.5 ; lift before move to center
M82 ; set extruder to absolute mode

Ending Script:
M104 S0 ; turn off extruder
M140 S0 ; turn off bed
G91 ; relative positioning
G1 Z10 F3000; up up and away
G90 ; absolute positioning
G1 X0 Y280 F3000 ; prepare for part removal
M84 ; disable motors
M106 S0 ; disable fan

remixed_from.title: Tiny Whoop gate. For Blade inductrix, tinywhoop, eachine E010 and others

title: Tiny Whoop Gate with LED Holder

description.text:
I printed the "Tiny Whoop gate. For Blade inductrix, tinywhoop, eachine E010 and others", and it was great. The only thing I was not happy with using Zip Ties or electric tape to hold the LED's in place. I thought this is 3D printed, it should be printed with everything installed.

So I made and printed an LED Clip. I did this to attach the LED's to the gates I had already printed. And if you already printed this gate, with out my modification, you can print the clip I made to hold your LED's in place. It will look much nicer than electric tape, and I think looks better than Zip Ties and with out the sharp tips that usually happen when cutting the end off a Zip Tie.

If you have not already printed this gate, you can print it with my modification and the LED's will slip on to each section and hold them in place with nothing extra added.

The way I attached the LED's is I just threaded them between the gate and the holder. I started in the middle of one side and just started feeding it through all the way around. I believe it took 63" of LED's to make it all the way around. I pulled the LED's all the way through the first holder until I could carefully wedge the wires under that holder. I then fed them all the way around until I got to the end, with about 1/4" to 1/2" extra. I then stuffed that extra under the end with the wire as best as I could. So far that has held the LED's in place good enough.

Hopefully it will work for you too and you will have as much success as I have had with them. Thanks Megabug for the original design :-)

description.text:
This is a nutcraker that I designed.
It consists of two pieces and works just like a skrew.
It works pretty good for hazelnuts and walnuts.
In order to use for bigger walnuts you should skale it by 120%.
You should choose a rather high infill to make the nutcracker stronger so that it does its duty without deforming or breaking. I printed it with 60% infill and it seems to work pretty good.

For the base, part number two, you can use supports depending on how good your printer handles bridges.
I tried it both with and without supports and it worked either way.
Althought it came out slightly better with supports.

title: Air Rocket Works launcher to Estes Air Rocket adapter

description.text:
This is a simple adapter to allow our Compressed Air Rocket launcher to work with other brand compressed air rockets. This is a simple print that slides over the end of our standard launch tube to make it the proper diameter to accept an Estes air rocket.

Also, remember that using a 1/2" NPT male thread to 3/8" NPT Female thread adapter and a 10-12" long length of pipe in place of our standard launch tube will allow you to launch Stomp Rocket brand rockets.

Fair warning - at higher pressures you may blow off the foam noses on these other brands...

Now go launch something!

This MIDI to CV converter is the perfect interface between your computer or iPad and an analog synthesizer (e.g., see https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2704888). It can independently drive up to three oscillators with 1V/octave CV inputs. (Connection to an iPad requires the USB camera adapter but is well worth it given the wide variety of great MIDI sequencer apps.)

This device has the following features:

  • USB MIDI Interface
  • Three channel Note CV output (88 keys, 1V/octave, MIDI channels 1-3) using a 12-bit DAC
  • Configurable note priority for each channel (Top Note, Bottom Note, or Last Note Priority)
  • Note scale factor calibration configurable in software
  • 5V Gate/Trigger outputs, where each channel can be independently configured to either output a gate (output high for entire length of time that note is on) or trigger (20 msec pulse each time a new note is initiated)
  • Velocity CV output (0 to 4V) for each channel
  • Pitch Bend CV output (0.5 +/- 0.5V), which can be configured for channel 1, 2, or 3
  • Control Change CV output (0 to 4V), which can be configured for channel 1, 2, or 3
  • OLED user interface, used for setting parameters and saving to EEPROM

This device uses the Teensy 2.0 USB development board. The schematics and assembly instructions can be found at: https://github.com/elkayem/usbMIDI2CV_MC.

The 3D printed panel must be printed with supports for the OLED screen mount. There is a recessed area on the back side of the panel that fits the screen mounting shape. I recommend picking up the screen by DIYMall, as the hole pattern was designed for that screen. Others may fit as well. Supports are not required for the case.

The panel includes raised text, and so must be printed with two colors. Most slicers include a "pause at height" plugin, which will move the hot end out of the way and allow you to switch filaments. The panels are 3mm thick, and the letters are 0.45mm thick. I printed with 0.15mm layer thickness, allowing the letters to be printed in three layers. Add the command to pause after you finish printing the 3mm layer, so you can change the filament color. (One tip: If you find that your printer is disabling the stepper motors after pausing, you may need to insert M84 S0 at the start of the G-Code. I did.)

Yes

description.text:
Three unique solutions to creating an "Impossible Dovetail" which can be disassembled and reassembled. Recesses on upper and lower surfaces of assembly give refuge to rare earth magnets. Magnets help keep set of three options together. Includes alignment features for stacking as well.

Three solutions:

  1. Center of rotation in the center of the square.
  2. Center of rotation aligned with short edge of cuboid.
  3. Center of rotation at an infinite distance.

These were printed on a uPrint. Still working on how to best print without the uPrint's soluble support system. I've printed this, on my Anet A8, with the dovetail facing upward and the stacking feature/magnet recess look terrible.
